    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-03-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-03-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="55"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d55">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 55.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hall</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States in Central
                                America</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-03-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 15, 1885</date>. (Received March
                        16.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Hall telegraphs the Department that the purport of its telegram to him of the
                    11th instant has been made known to the President of Guatemala, who appears to
                    be deeply impressed, saying that although he sends an army to the frontier of
                    Salvador to support the movements in favor of the Union he has no intention to
                    invade neighboring states.</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>Mr. Hall is of opinion that if Mexico will for the present remain passive,
                    affording the President of Guatemala an opportunity of receding decorously,
                    bloodshed may be avoided.</p>
            </div>
